20" id=3D"definition"></button><div class=3D"content-container xl:px-0 bg-w=
hite"><div class=3D"w-full overflow-hidden"><h2 class=3D"mb-6">What is a p-=
value?</h2><div class=3D"PortableText_page-builder__oGx0w guide-body long-f=
orm-rich-text"><p>A p-value determines whether an experiment's results are =
likely real or a fluke.</p><p>P-values are probabilities, meaning they can =
take any value between 0 and 1. The smaller the p-value (i.e., closer to ze=
ro), the more confident you can be that the results aren=E2=80=99t just ran=
dom chance.</p><p>In web and product testing, p-values help you separate me=
aningful changes from noise when tweaking websites, apps, or <a href=3D"htt=
ps://amplitude.com/blog/ultimate-guide-product-feature-analysis" class=3D"b=
tn-text" aria-label=3D"product features">product features</a>.</p><p>Say yo=
u change the color of your website's =E2=80=9CBuy Now=E2=80=9D button. A p-=
value can tell you whether any increase in sales is likely due to your chan=
ge or if it=E2=80=99s a normal, day-to-day variation.</p><p>However, it=E2=
=80=99s important to remember that p-values can=E2=80=99t prove anything wi=
th 100% certainty=E2=80=94they instead give you a strong idea of how likely=
 it is that your results are meaningful. This insight makes p-values (used =
alongside other calculations) a crucial part of the decision-making toolkit=
 for anyone running experiments or <a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/glossar=
y/terms/analytics" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"analyzing">analyzing</a=
> data.</p><h3 id=3D"p-values-vs-confidence-intervals">P-values vs confiden=
ce intervals</h3><p>P-values and confidence intervals are two sides of the =
same coin. Both values can help you understand your data, but they do so in=
 slightly different ways.</p><p>P-values tell us how likely our results are=
 if there=E2=80=99s no real effect=E2=80=94they measure probability.</p><p>=
Confidence intervals, on the other hand, give us a range where the true eff=
ect lies. The value is an estimation rather than a set number.</p><p>Experi=
ments can use p-values and confidence intervals. The results help you make =
more informed decisions about your product and website.</p><p>Imagine you=
=E2=80=99re testing a new site feature:</p><ul><li>A p-value of 0.03 indica=
tes that there=E2=80=99s only a 3% chance you=E2=80=99d see these results i=
f the feature had no effect.</li><li>A 95% confidence interval of 2% to 8% =
suggests that you=E2=80=99re pretty sure the feature increases engagement b=
etween 2% and 8%.</li></ul><p>Using both values provides you with a more co=
mplete picture. The p-value tells you if there=E2=80=99s likely an effect, =
while the confidence interval gives you an idea of how big that effect migh=
t be.</p><p>You can use these tools to decide whether that new feature or p=
roduct update is worth the investment. Is the potential increase in engagem=
ent worth the risk and effort? Or do you need to go back to the drawing boa=
rd? P-values provide a practical framework for making these decisions.</p><=
/div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-toc-section-key=3D"45962=
