=3D"absolute -top-20" id=3D"hypothesis-testing"></button><div class=3D"cont=
ent-container xl:px-0 bg-white"><div class=3D"w-full overflow-hidden"><h2 c=
lass=3D"mb-6">The role of p-values in hypothesis testing</h2><div class=3D"=
PortableText_page-builder__oGx0w guide-body long-form-rich-text"><p>P-value=
s are an essential part of hypothesis testing, a method for determining whe=
ther changes to a product have a meaningful impact.</p><p>The process start=
s with questions like =E2=80=9CDoes this change make a difference?=E2=80=9D=
</p><p>You then set up two hypotheses:</p><ul><li><strong>Null hypothesis</=
strong>: There=E2=80=99s no real effect (the skeptical stance)</li><li><str=
ong>Alternative hypothesis</strong>: There is a real effect.</li></ul><p>Af=
ter you run the experiment and collect data, you calculate the p-value. Thi=
s value helps answer the question: =E2=80=9CIf there was no effect, how lik=
ely are we to see these results?=E2=80=9D</p><p>If the p-value is small (us=
ually less than 0.05), you might conclude that the results are unlikely und=
er the null hypothesis, leading you to accept the alternative hypothesis.</=
p><p>The process helps you decide whether or not to implement changes. For =
example, when testing a new layout, your null hypothesis would be =E2=80=9C=
The new layout doesn=E2=80=99t affect user engagement.=E2=80=9D</p><p>After=
 the test, you might get a p-value of 0.02. This value suggests there is on=
ly a 2% chance of observing the results if the layout truly had no effect. =
Based on this information, you might decide the new layout positively impac=
ts engagement and roll out the change.</p><p>However, a low p-value alone d=
oesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean the new layout is better=E2=80=94it simply =
indicates that the difference in results is probably not due to chance. The=
 improvement could be due to other factors you hadn=E2=80=99t considered (w=
hich you can find and eliminate with other tests).</p><p>Consider this anal=
ogy: You hear a noise at night. Your null hypothesis is =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s just the wind.=E2=80=9D A low p-value is like saying, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s very unlikely to hear this noise if it=E2=80=99s just the wind.=E2=
=80=9D The value suggests it=E2=80=99s probably not the wind, but it doesn=
=E2=80=99t prove it=E2=80=99s a burglar (your alternative hypothesis). The =
noise could be your cat, a tree branch, or something else entirely.</p><p>T=
his slight difference matters because it keeps us humble and open to other =
explanations. Statistics guide our decisions, but they don=E2=80=99t make t=
hem for us. You must still use your judgment, consider other evidence, and =
be open to alternative explanations.</p><p>In summary, hypothesis testing w=
ith p-values is vital for helping product teams make quick, data-driven dec=
isions. However, it=E2=80=99s always wise to combine the results with other=
 evidence, such as user feedback, long-term trends, and practical considera=
tions, such as how the change aligns with your <a href=3D"https://amplitude=
.com/blog/product-strategy-framework" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"prod=
uct strategy">product strategy</a> and the cost of implementation.</p></div=
></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-toc-section-key=3D"2f22a1add=
20d"><div><div class=3D"relative max-h-0" style=3D"top: -132px;"><button cl=
