lass=3D"content-container xl:px-0 bg-white"><div class=3D"w-full overflow-h=
idden"><h2 class=3D"mb-6">Interpreting p-values: Significance levels and de=
cision-making</h2><div class=3D"PortableText_page-builder__oGx0w guide-body=
 long-form-rich-text"><p>Interpreting p-values is crucial for making decisi=
ons after your experiments. Making sense of them helps you see if your resu=
lts are significant and if you should reject the null hypothesis.</p><p>The=
 most common significance level used in testing is 0.05. This level means t=
hat if your p-value is less than 0.05, your results are typically considere=
d statistically significant. In other words, there=E2=80=99s less than a 5%=
 chance you=E2=80=99d see these results if there was no real effect.</p><p>=
But interpretation doesn=E2=80=99t just involve looking for that 0.05 mark.=
</p><ul><li>p &lt; 0.01: strong evidence against the null hypothesis</li><l=
i>0.01 &lt; p &lt; 0.05: moderate evidence against the null hypothesis</li>=
<li>0.05 &lt; p &lt; 0.1: weak evidence against the null hypothesis</li><li=
>p &gt; 0.1: little or no evidence against the null hypothesis</li></ul><p>=
The strength of evidence needed also depends on the stakes of your experime=
nt. For instance, a p-value of 0.04 might be enough to try a new feature, b=
ut you may want a lower p-value before making a major change to your core p=
roduct.</p><p><a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/explore/experiment/statistic=
al-significance-guide" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"Statistical signifi=
cance">Statistical significance</a> doesn=E2=80=99t always mean <em>practic=
al </em>significance. A tiny change might be statistically significant in a=
 large sample but not worth implementing if it doesn=E2=80=99t have a meani=
ngful impact.</p><p>You should also be wary of p-hacking, i.e., running too=
 many tests and only reporting the significant ones. This practice can lead=
 to false positives and misleading conclusions.</p><p>P-values <em>assist <=
/em>your decision-making=E2=80=94they=E2=80=99re not a rule. Use them with =
<a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/explore/metrics/what-are-metrics-guide" cl=
ass=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"metrics">metrics</a> like effect sizes, conf=
idence intervals, and your business knowledge to make the best choices for =
your product or website.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div =
