8 section-container xl:px-0"><button class=3D"absolute -top-20" id=3D"examp=
les"></button><div class=3D"content-container xl:px-0 bg-white"><div class=
=3D"w-full overflow-hidden"><h2 class=3D"mb-6">Real-world examples of p-val=
ue application</h2><div class=3D"PortableText_page-builder__oGx0w guide-bod=
y long-form-rich-text"><p>P-values guide decisions across various aspects o=
f products, from design elements to core business strategies. Let=E2=80=99s=
 examine how p-values apply in practice.</p><h3 id=3D"ecommerce-button-colo=
r">Ecommerce button color</h3><p>An <a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/indust=
ry/ecommerce" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"online clothing store">onlin=
e clothing store</a> tests green vs. blue =E2=80=9CAdd to Cart=E2=80=9D but=
tons. After a week-long A/B test with 50,000 visitors split evenly between =
the two versions, the green button shows a 2% higher click-through rate (22=
% vs. 20%) with a p-value of 0.03.</p><p>This p-value suggests there=E2=80=
=99s only a 3% chance of seeing this difference if the button colors were e=
qually effective. The marketing team decided to implement the green button,=
 estimating it could increase sales.</p><h3 id=3D"app-onboarding-flow">App =
onboarding flow</h3><p>A fitness tracking app experiments with a new <a hre=
f=3D"https://amplitude.com/guides/measure-user-onboarding" class=3D"btn-tex=
t" aria-label=3D"user onboarding">user onboarding</a> process that includes=
 more visual guides and fewer steps. Over a month, 10,000 new users are ran=
domly assigned to the old or new process.</p><p>The completion rate increas=
es from 60% to 65%, with a p-value of 0.001. This low p-value gives strong =
confidence that the new process is better. The product team rolls out the c=
hange and projects it will lead to a higher number of active users.</p><h3 =
id=3D"email-subject-line-test">Email subject line test</h3><p>A <a href=3D"=
https://amplitude.com/industry/b2b-saas" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"B=
2B software company">B2B software company</a> tests two email subject lines=
 for its monthly newsletter. With a sample size of 20,000 subscribers split=
 evenly, open rates differ by 1% (22% vs. 21%), but the p-value is 0.2.</p>=
<p>This high p-value indicates that the difference might be due to chance. =
The marketing team chooses to run a longer test with more variation before =
making any changes.</p><h3 id=3D"website-loading-speed">Website loading spe=
ed</h3><p>After optimizing images and scripts, an e-learning platform=E2=80=
=99s average load time decreases from 3.5 to 3.0 seconds.</p><p>In a two-we=
ek test period with 100,000 visitors, <a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/book=
s/user-engagement" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"user engagement">user e=
ngagement</a> (measured by average session duration) increases by 5%, from =
10 minutes to 10.5 minutes, with a p-value of 0.07. This p-value is in the =
=E2=80=9Cweak evidence=E2=80=9D range.</p><p>As a result, the development t=
eam opts to keep the optimizations but continues monitoring to see if the e=
ngagement increase becomes more statistically significant over time.</p><h3=
 id=3D"pricing-strategy">Pricing strategy</h3><p>A project management compa=
ny tests a new mid-tier pricing option between its basic and premium plans.=
 Over two months, it exposes 50% of its 10,000 monthly website visitors to =
the new pricing structure.</p><p><a href=3D"https://amplitude.com/glossary/=
terms/conversion-rate" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"Conversions">Conver=
sions</a> (free trial sign-ups) increased by 10% in the test group, with a =
p-value of 0.04. This number is just under the standard 0.05 threshold, so =
the product team decided to launch the new pricing tier gradually=E2=80=94i=
t starts with 20% of new visitors while closely monitoring long-term <a hre=
f=3D"https://amplitude.com/blog/customer-lifetime-value" class=3D"btn-text"=
 aria-label=3D"customer value">customer value</a> metrics.</p></div></div><=
/div></div></div></div></div><div data-toc-section-key=3D"a4613ec7a7dc"><di=
v><div class=3D"relative max-h-0" style=3D"top: -132px;"><button class=3D"a=
bsolute max-h-0" id=3D"toc-chapter-a4613ec7a7dc"></button></div><div class=
=3D""><div class=3D"GuideChapterSectionView_guide-text__S_vvz bg-white pt-4=
 lg:pt-8 pb-4 lg:pb-8 section-container xl:px-0"><button class=3D"absolute =
-top-20" id=3D"misconceptions "></button><div class=3D"content-container xl=
:px-0 bg-white"><div class=3D"w-full overflow-hidden"><h2 class=3D"mb-6">Co=
mmon misconceptions about p-values</h2><div class=3D"PortableText_page-buil=
der__oGx0w guide-body long-form-rich-text"><p>P-values are often misunderst=
ood, even by experienced researchers and those who use them regularly.</p><=
p>These misconceptions can lead to poor decisions. You might overhaul your =
website based on a =E2=80=9Csignificant=E2=80=9D result that=E2=80=99s tiny=
 in practical terms or miss out on a promising feature because your test wa=
s underpowered.</p><p>Understanding these nuances helps you accurately inte=
rpret your A/B tests and other experiments, leading to better product decis=
ions.</p><p>Let=E2=80=99s clear up some common myths.</p><ul><li><strong>=
=E2=80=9CA low p-value proves my hypothesis is true.=E2=80=9D </strong>Not =
quite. A low p-value just means your data is unlikely if the null hypothesi=
s is true. It doesn=E2=80=99t prove your specific alternative hypothesis.</=
li></ul><ul><li><strong>=E2=80=9CP-values measure the probability that my r=
esults occurred by chance.=E2=80=9D </strong>The values measure the probabi=
lity of seeing such results (or more extreme) if the null hypothesis were t=
rue=E2=80=94a subtle but important difference.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>=E2=
=80=9CA non-significant p-value means there=E2=80=99s no effect.=E2=80=9D</=
strong> This statement isn=E2=80=99t necessarily true. The value might just=
 mean you don=E2=80=99t have enough evidence to detect an effect. Maybe you=
r sample size was too small, for instance.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>=E2=80=
=9CP-values tell me how important results are.=E2=80=9D </strong>The values=
 only speak to statistical significance, not practical importance. A tiny, =
meaningful effect can have a very low p-value in a large sample.</li></ul><=
ul><li><strong>=E2=80=9CIf p &lt; 0.05, the effect is real; if p &gt; 0.05,=
 it isn=E2=80=99t.=E2=80=9D </strong>This idea treats p-values as a binary =
switch, which they=E2=80=99re not. P-values are more like a continuous meas=
ure of evidence against the null hypothesis.</li></ul></div></div></div></d=
iv></div></div></div><div data-toc-section-key=3D"e0755fcf1b19"><div><div c=
lass=3D"relative max-h-0" style=3D"top: -132px;"><button class=3D"absolute =
max-h-0" id=3D"toc-chapter-e0755fcf1b19"></button></div><div class=3D""><di=
v class=3D"GuideChapterSectionView_guide-text__S_vvz bg-white pt-4 lg:pt-8 =
pb-4 lg:pb-8 section-container xl:px-0"><button class=3D"absolute -top-20" =
id=3D"limitations"></button><div class=3D"content-container xl:px-0 bg-whit=
e"><div class=3D"w-full overflow-hidden"><h2 class=3D"mb-6">Limitations and=
 criticisms </h2><div class=3D"PortableText_page-builder__oGx0w guide-body =
long-form-rich-text"><p>Although p-values are widely used in experiments, t=
hey have drawbacks.</p><ul><li><strong>Overreliance</strong>: Many product =
teams focus too heavily on p-values, sometimes ignoring other important asp=
ects of their data.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Arbitrary thresholds</strong>:=
 The typical 0.05 significance level is somewhat arbitrary and can lead to =
thinking in black-and-white about more complex results.</li></ul><ul><li><s=
trong>Doesn=E2=80=99t measure effect size</strong>: A low p-value doesn=E2=
=80=99t tell whether an effect is large or important. Small, practically in=
significant effects can have low p-values in large samples.</li></ul><ul><l=
i><strong>Vulnerable to p-hacking</strong>: Researchers can manipulate anal=
yses to achieve significant p-values, leading to false positives. This prac=
tice is especially tempting in fast-paced testing environments.</li></ul><u=
l><li><strong>Sample size sensitivity</strong>: With larger datasets (commo=
n in web experiments), almost everything becomes =E2=80=9Cstatistically sig=
nificant.=E2=80=9D</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Doesn=E2=80=99t work well for m=
ultiple comparisons</strong>: When you run many tests, which is typical in =
product refinements, the chance of false positives increases.</li></ul><ul>=
<li><strong>Encourages binary thinking</strong>: P-values can lead to overs=
implified =E2=80=9Csignificant or not=E2=80=9D decisions rather than nuance=
d interpretations.</li></ul><p>These limitations are why you shouldn=E2=80=
=99t rely on p-values alone. A slight tweak to a website might yield a stat=
istically significant result but have no real impact on <a href=3D"https://=
amplitude.com/blog/user-behavior" class=3D"btn-text" aria-label=3D"user beh=
avior">user behavior</a> or business metrics.</p><p>Recognizing these criti=
cisms enables you to use p-values as part of your broader decision-making r=
esources rather than as the sole judge of truth in your experiments.</p></d=
